    {{#box}}




A parent wants to ship a rectangular package (with dimensions x, y, z) to their child.  The shipping company  requires that the sum of the girth and length of the box (2x+2y+z) is at most {{constraint}} inches.









                What is the  maximum volume of a box that can be shipped, and what could it's dimensions be?





                   We attempt to maximize f(x,y,z)={{f}} subject to g(x,y,z)={{g}}={{constraint}}.



The maximum volume is {{maxvalue}} cubic inches, which occurs at (x,y,z, \lambda)={{maxsolns}}.









    {{/box}}



    {{#silo}}




A farmer is building a grain silo intended to hold {{constraint}}\pi cubic meters of grain.  The silo has a cylindrical body with radius r meters and height h meters, with a hemispheric dome with radius r meters.  The cost of materials for the floor is ${{floor}} per square meter, but the cost of materials for the dome is ${{dome}} per square meter, and the cost of building the side is ${{wall}} per square meter.









                What is the  minimum cost of constructing this silo, and what could it's dimensions be?



(Note that the dome ceiling also contains grain.  Also recall that a sphere has volume \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3 and surface area 4\pi r^2.)





                   We attempt to minimize f(r,h)=\pi({{f}}) subject to g(r,h)=\pi ({{g}})=\pi{{constraint}}.



The minimum is ${{maxvalue}}\pi, which occurs at (x,y,z, \lambda)={{maxsolns}}.









    {{/silo}}



